To deploy a containerized application on AWS ECS, you can follow these steps:

1. Register an external instance to your cluster if you want to run workloads on external instances [Source: aws/ECS/Running workloads on external instances].
2. Create a task definition and use the `requiresCompatibilities` parameter to validate that it is compatible with your external instances or EC2 instances [Source: aws/ECS/Running workloads on external instances].
3. Choose a launch type, either Fargate (serverless pay-as-you-go) or EC2 (configure and deploy EC2 instances in your cluster), depending on your application architecture needs [Source: aws/ECS/Application architecture].
4. Use the AWS CDK to define a containerized web server on Fargate, as shown in the example code block [Source: aws/ECS/Getting started with Amazon ECS using the AWS CDK > Step 2: Use the AWS CDK to define a containerized web server on Fargate].

For example, you can use the following AWS CDK code to deploy a containerized web server on Fargate:
```
import * as cdk from 'aws-cdk-lib';
import * as ecs from 'aws-cdk-lib/aws-ecs';

export class MyStack extends cdk.Stack {
  constructor(scope: cdk.Construct, id: string, props?: cdk.StackProps) {
    super(scope, id, props);

    const taskDefinition = new ecs.TaskDefinition(this, 'TaskDefinition', {
      family: 'my-task-definition',
      requiresCompatibilities: [ecs.Compatibility.FARGATE],
    });

    const container = taskDefinition.addContainer('MyContainer', {
      image: ecs.ContainerImage.fromDockerHub('amazon/amazon-ecs-sample'),
    });
  }
}
```
Note that this is just an example, and you should adjust the code to fit your specific needs.

